	(text "In general there could be two potential leakage sources: from the control voltage (coil or LED) and from the VB.\n\nLet's generously say that on an off channel, the coil or LED will be at a maximum of 10mV from IR drop in the GNDD\ntrace.\n\nTLP170J isolation resistance is 5e10 minimum, giving 0.2pA, which really disappears into 100k.\n\nRelay insulation resistance is 1e10. Clearly VB through the relay could dominate.\n\nFINISH THIS ANALYSIS - NOT CHECKED BELOW\n\n* Off current is typically 1nA, worst case 1000nA, at 600V.\n\nWe are only at 60V, but even if we take 1000nA, times 100k this is 240uV.\n\nThe relay resistance is 1E10. This gives 2.4fA through the relay.\n\nNote we don't consider coil to contact, since OFF state voltage is low."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 19.304 194.31 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "3490d9e8-08ba-4b47-9a75-16c6a9d468b4")
	)
	(text "Current to \nactivate diode"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 205.74 91.44 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "3a620aee-a5cc-4d35-8c9d-6c43137b3ec6")
	)
	(text "12V on 1k = 144mW"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 160.02 52.578 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
		)
		(uuid "3c2b37c6-6961-49fa-860f-d83512cade64")
	)
	(text "100V, 100K \n= 0.1W"
